    'tag%3Agoogle.com%2C2005%3Areader/item/eef77208d409184b.html':'<div>Each month in the Big Picture, we post a collection of photographs from Afghanistan.\xa0 They feature American forces and those of other countries, and they show us daily life among the Afghan people.\xa0 In June, President Obama declared that the United States had largely achieved its goals in Afghanistan, which set in motion an aggressive timetable for the withdrawal of American troops. However, the fighting has spiked in some regions of the country. On Aug. 6, the United States suffered its deadliest day in the nearly decade-long war when insurgents shot down a Chinook transport helicopter, killing 30 Americans and eight Afghans.\xa0 According to the United Nations, 360 Afghan civilians were killed in June alone.\xa0 The\xa0surges of violence reflect how deeply entrenched the insurgency remains even far from its strongholds. The war continues.\xa0 -- <em>Paula Nelson</em> (<a href="http://www.boston.com/bigpicture/2011/08/afghanistan_august_2011.html">42 photos total</a>)</div><div><a name="photo1"></a><a href="http://www.boston.com/bigpicture/2011/08/afghanistan_august_2011.html"><img src="http://inapcache.boston.com/universal/site_graphics/blogs/bigpicture/afghanistan_082011/bp1.jpg" style="height:660px;width:990px"></a><br><div>Villager Juma Khan meets with the provincial district governor and fellow villagers at a shura, or consultation, on July 23 at the US Marine Patrol Base Salaam Bazaar in Helmand province, Afghanistan. As mentors with the international coalition attempt to phase out their involvement and put Afghan institutions in the lead, the Taliban continue to gain strength in  many of Helmand\'s northern communities, where legitimate Afghan governance is more of a plan than a reality. (David Goldman/Associated Press) <div></div></div></div>\n<br style="clear:both">\n<br style="clear:both">\n  <a style="font-size:10px;color:maroon" href="http://www.pheedcontent.com/hostedMorselCl